\description{
Converts a ggplot2 plot whose layers are drawn from sf objects (or, for
\code{\link[ggplot2:geom_point]{ggplot2::geom_point()}}, \code{\link[ggplot2:geom_path]{ggplot2::geom_path()}}, \code{\link[ggplot2:geom_line]{ggplot2::geom_line()}}
and \code{\link[ggplot2:geom_polygon]{ggplot2::geom_polygon()}}, from plain data frames) into a QGIS
project (\code{.qgs}) file. The data of each layer is saved as a GeoPackage
under \verb{<path minus extension>_data/}, and the layer is styled after the
plot's trained color scale:
}
\details{
\itemize{
\item a continuous \code{fill}/\code{colour} scale becomes a graduated renderer with
fine-grained equal-interval classes (or a continuously interpolated
color, see \code{gradient_style}),
\item a binned one (e.g. \code{\link[ggplot2:scale_fill_steps]{ggplot2::scale_fill_steps()}}) becomes a graduated
renderer with one class per bin, using the scale's exact bin
boundaries and colors,
\item a discrete one becomes a categorized renderer,
\item a layer with no \code{fill}/\code{colour} mapping becomes a single symbol with
the color ggplot2 would have used.
}

Following ggplot2's semantics for polygons, \code{fill} is the interior and
\code{colour} is the border: a \code{colour} scale on a polygon layer colors the
outlines while the interior keeps the constant fill. Constant outline
colors and widths are taken from the plot as well. Mapping both \code{fill}
and \code{colour} on the same layer is not supported.

Only a bare column name is supported for the \code{fill}/\code{colour} aesthetics;
a constant or a computed expression (e.g. \code{aes(fill = AREA * 2)}) is an
error.
}
\section{Data frame layers}{
A \code{geom_point()}, \code{geom_path()}, \code{geom_line()} or \code{geom_polygon()} layer
drawn from a plain data frame is converted to an sf layer: one point per
row, or one linestring/polygon per group (ggplot2's grouping — an
explicit \code{group} aesthetic or the interaction of the discrete
aesthetics; \code{geom_line()} orders each line by \code{x} like ggplot2 does,
and polygon rings are closed). The plot must use \code{\link[ggplot2:coord_sf]{ggplot2::coord_sf()}},
and the \code{x}/\code{y} values are taken to be coordinates in the panel CRS:
\code{coord_sf()}'s \code{crs} argument if given, otherwise the CRS of the first
sf layer (\code{coord_sf(default_crs = )} is not supported). Like
\code{fill}/\code{colour}, the \code{x}/\code{y} aesthetics must be bare column names, and
the layer must use the identity stat and position.

A point layer keeps every column of the data frame as attributes; a
line/polygon layer keeps the columns that are constant within every
group, one feature per group (a mapped \code{fill}/\code{colour} column must be
constant within each group). \code{fill = NA}/\code{colour = NA} (including
\code{geom_polygon()}'s default \code{colour}) render as "not drawn" in QGIS.
The \code{size}, \code{shape}, \code{linetype} and \code{alpha} aesthetics are not carried
over; those symbol properties keep the QGIS defaults.

The project opens zoomed to the plot's displayed range (the panel range,
including the default expansion and any \code{\link[ggplot2:coord_sf]{ggplot2::coord_sf()}} \code{xlim}/
\code{ylim}), reprojected to the project CRS, rather than the whole world.
}

\section{tmap plots}{
A tmap (>= 4.4) object with vector layers is converted the same way:
\code{tm_polygons()}/\code{tm_fill()}/\code{tm_borders()}, \code{tm_lines()}, and
\code{tm_symbols()}/\code{tm_dots()}/\code{tm_bubbles()}/\code{tm_squares()} (on point data)
are supported, including \code{\link[tmap:qtm]{tmap::qtm()}} maps. The color scales are
reproduced from tmap's own trained scales:
\itemize{
\item \code{\link[tmap:tm_scale_intervals]{tmap::tm_scale_intervals()}} (any classification style) becomes a
graduated renderer with tmap's exact break boundaries and colors
(zero-width bins from tied breaks are collapsed; the continuous-style
legend variants, \code{label.style}, are not supported),
\item \code{\link[tmap:tm_scale_categorical]{tmap::tm_scale_categorical()}} and \code{\link[tmap:tm_scale_ordinal]{tmap::tm_scale_ordinal()}} become a
categorized renderer keyed by the raw data values (missing values
become the "all other values" category); tmap's formatted legend
labels are not carried over,
\item \code{\link[tmap:tm_scale_continuous]{tmap::tm_scale_continuous()}} (including the transformed variants,
approximated with piecewise-linear color stops) becomes a graduated
renderer with 25 equal-interval classes, or an exact continuous
gradient with \code{gradient_style = "continuous"}.
}

A layer maps either \code{fill} or \code{col} to a data column (not both); other
visual constants (symbol size, line type, alpha) keep the QGIS defaults.
Layers sharing one \code{\link[tmap:tm_shape]{tmap::tm_shape()}} share one GeoPackage: the data is
written once and every layer of the shape references the same table.

QGIS's graduated renderers have no missing-value class, so for an
intervals/continuous scale the features whose value is missing go to a
separate layer named \code{"<layer> (missing value)"}, drawn in tmap's
\code{value.na} color directly below its parent layer (the same GeoPackage
table, filtered with the QGIS provider filter \verb{"column" IS NULL}). Set
\code{create_na_layer = FALSE} to leave the missing features undrawn
instead. Categorical scales render missing values within their own
layer (the "all other values" category), so they never get the extra
layer. \code{\link[tmap:tm_basemap]{tmap::tm_basemap()}} layers become XYZ tile layers
(overriding the \code{basemap} argument): a URL template is used as is, a
provider name is resolved via \code{\link[maptiles:get_providers]{maptiles::get_providers()}}, and with
several basemaps only the first one is checked (visible) in the layer
tree. Rasters, facets, \code{tm_text()} and the other scale types are errors.

The project CRS defaults to the tmap display CRS (\code{use_plot_crs = TRUE}
for tmap objects): \code{\link[tmap:tm_crs]{tmap::tm_crs()}} or the main shape's CRS — or
EPSG:3857 when the map has basemaps, which is how tmap itself resolves
it — so the project opens looking like the tmap plot, zoomed to the
main shape's bounding box. \code{use_plot_crs = FALSE} forces EPSG:3857.

The conversion relies on tmap internals that are not part of its public
API, so a tmap version older than 4.4 is rejected.
}

